questions.question:
Consider the following scheme for implementing a critical section in a situation with three processes Pi, Pj, and Pk.

Pi:
  repeat
    flag[i] := true;
    while flag[j] or flag[k] do
      case turn of
        j: if flag[j] then
             begin
               flag[i] := false;
               while turn != i do skip;
               flag[i] := true;
             end;
        k: if flag[k] then
             begin
               flag[i] := false;
               while turn != i do skip;
               flag[i] := true;
             end;
      end; {case}
    end; {while}
    critical section
    if turn = j then turn := k
    else turn := j;
    flag[i] := false
  non-critical section
  until false;

A. Does the scheme ensure mutual exclusion in the critical section? Briefly explain.
B. Is there a situation in which a waiting process can never enter the critical section? If so, explain and suggest modifications to the code to solve this problem.

A. Yes, the scheme ensures mutual exclusion
B. No starvation can occur in this scheme
C. Yes, mutual exclusion is ensured; but starvation is possible — a waiting process may never enter the critical section
D. No, mutual exclusion is NOT guaranteed

